, swarthy’ and is the probable source of most of the examples in Domesday Book. In the northern and eastern counties of England settled by Vikings in the 10th and 11th centuries, alternative sources are Old Norse <i>Kolr</i> and <i>Koli</i> (either from a nickname ‘the swarthy one’ or a short form of names in <i>Kol-</i>), and Old Norse <i>Kollr</i> (from a nickname, perhaps ‘the bald one’).","English: nickname for someone with swarthy skin or black hair, from Middle English <i>col</i>, coul(e) ‘charcoal, coal’ (Old English <i>col</i>)."]},{"name":"Cowling","meanings":["variant of   Colling  .","habitational name from either of two places called Cowling, in Yorkshire and North Yorkshire. The former is named with Old English <i>coll</i> ‘hill-top’ + the placename forming suffix <i>-ing</i>, meaning ‘hill-top place’.","variant of   Cooling  ."]},{"name":"Culling","meanings":["English (Norfolk): from the Middle English personal name <i>Culling</i>, perhaps to be identified with   Colling  ."]},{"name":"Collinge","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Colling  ."]},{"name":"Kolling","meanings":["German (<b>Kölling</b>): from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Kolo</i>, <i>Colo</i> + the suffix <i>-ing</i> denoting affiliation.","North German: topographic name from Middle Low German <i>kolinge</i>, a term denoting an area of forest to be cut for charcoal burning. Compare   Colling  ."]}]},{"name":"Dororthy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Dorothea .  The name was not used in the Middle Ages, but was taken up in the 15th century and became common thereafter. It was borne by the American film star  Dorothy Lamour  (  1914–1996 , born  Dorothy Kaumeyer )."],"variants":[{"name":"Dorothee","meanings":["Usual English form of   Dorothea .  The name was not used in the Middle Ages, but was taken up in the 15th century and became common thereafter. It was 